Horace from the first seems to have wisely determined to keep himself free from those shackles which most men are so eager to forge for themselves, by setting their heart on wealth and social distinction. With perfect sincerity he had told MaecenaS, as we have seen, that he coveted neither, and he gives his reasons thus (SatireS, Ι. 6) :—-
